column1: The responses of this survey will not be beneficial because of how questions are asked. You are asked to rank values from 1-5 but it allows you to make everything most important rather than ranking from most to least important where you must make tradeoffs. It also restricts you to choose only one preferred alternative without comment - I like two but think they both need revisions/modifications.

column1: If I weren't frequently traveling on 345 I would have had no idea about this public survey. I saw it on TxDOT signage a few days ago and kept forgetting to go online once I got home. WHY hasn't a mailing been sent to every household south of downtown? Including mailers to suburbs south of Dallas? Those desiring to eliminate 345 seem to have no understanding of those of us who live south of downtown and travel into Dallas on a frequent basis. I use 345 very often and it's helpful, simpler and faster (unless there is an accident) than using Woodall Rogers or the tollway or I-35. I cannot even imagine the traffic congestion if 345 is eliminated. I understand people must still be upset that 345 was built thru some neighborhoods decades ago. But the impact on those neighborhoods has happened long ago and eliminating 345 won't bring them back. But eliminating 345 WILL impact people traveling from south of downtown thru downtown and northward. As is typical with Dallas, south of the Trinity barely exists in planners' minds likely because they don't live south.  The recent change in how to enter the tollway from south of downtown is terrible in my opinion. And what they are making drivers do to enter the tollway from westbound woodall rogers is a complete disaster. Exit 35 at Oak Lawn, wait thru a light or two, make a left turn to now enter the tollway? Ridiculous. PLEASE leave 345 alone and don't give us another alleged "improvement".  It's fine and useful as it is.

column1:
Until today I wasn't even aware there was a discussion to change this critical Interstate due to pedestrian & bicycling complaints. I would propose TxDOT actually expand the I-345 to give better access/dedicated ramp for the freight trucks who use this freeway from I-30 to Hwy75. Currently they are forced to cross multiple lanes of off ramp traffic to merge onto I-345 to gain access to Hwy 75 North. 

This is an excellent thoroughfare and desperately needed for our quickly growing Metroplex. It is our gasoline and freight hauling taxes than pay for these roads; not the bottled water the cyclist's carry around.  They might complain the loudest but do not pay the bills!

column5: Travel to/from medical & hospital facilities. Travel to/from shopping centers. The actual freeway has multiple lane but the on/off ramps need to be expanded to multi-lane to ease congestion.

column1: Your questions here bias the survey respondents by ignoring the proven fact and reality of induced demand by highways.  LA has shown that you can build ever more huge highways and it will only create more demand for them, leading to increased congestion, pollution, smog, bad air quality, and lower quality of life for everyone trying to live and work around these highways. It also does not explain the major success and benefits that have been reaped by cities like San Francisco when they removed highways that used to cut through their city. Without this context many regular people have the scientifically proven incorrect view that highways can "solve" problems that they cannot solve, without understanding the proven benefits of removing them because they haven't been made aware of them.

column1: The data presented at the meeting on June 22 was somewhat misleading, particularly with regards to the information about the traffic impact on the I-345 alternatives. The charts presented an analysis of overall traffic increase/decrease as a percentage of current levels (e.g. "would raise street traffic by 35%") without accounting for overall volume. So the removal option, which would be the most environmentally friendly as well as providing access and community connection in the downtown area, was presented as increasing the local traffic by a dramatic amount, although the comparatively smaller volume of traffic would still be manageable. Nor did this graphs attempt to account for alternative routes instead of the I-345 corridor, again guiding viewers toward a pre-determined option rather than a direct comparison of the choices.

column1: Target commuters using 345 at different times of day using license plate scanning technology. Much of the depressed 345 lobby does not use 345 for commuting purposes. Their focus is on economic development and neighborhood linkage. As one who uses the Green Line and walks to Deep Ellum, the barrier created by 345 and the entrance-exit ramps could be relatively easily addressed by improved sidewalks and designing local streets and ramps for pedestrian crossing. Care must be taken to prevent a new 345 from reducing access to jobs from the Southern Sector.  There is significant land for new TOD and economic development even without shrinking 345 . The worse ideal is to end 345 north of I-30 using local streets for traffic distribution. The traffic volume will dramatically worsen pedestrian, bike and transit travel.

column24: I hope that it will be. Please provide updates on a regular basis. I use this corridor every day two times daily, to transit the area to and from uptown. Congestion is tolerable each day. I am concerned that if there is no solution prior to removal, the area will become like New Your City with traffic at a standstill every day all day long. This is not what Dallas needs. Dallas needs a smooth and streamlined corridor to get traffic through to the north and south without rerouting to other congested freeways or placing additional burden on the local streets further straining the current roadways that are not designed at this time to handle additional traffic loading.

column17: The Removal of the I-345 will make the surrounding streets safer by eliminating traffic exiting the highway. The removal of I-345 is the only available option which does not inhibit the movement of bicycle and pedestrian traffic between Downtown and Deep Ellum, as well as Downtown and Old East Dallas. The Removal of I-345 will significantly simplify construction and planning for DART's D2 subway project, as well as any future transportation projects crossing the current I-345 right of way. Because the other build options add northbound capacity, they will induce demand along I-345, likely leading to greater congestion. Spending money to expand urban highway infrastructure is an irresponsible use of local, state, or federal funds, given that pedestrian, bicycle, and public transit infrastructure is underdeveloped in these areas, and transportation by these modes is unimaginably more environmentally sustainable than transportation by road. The removal of I-345 will make travel along this corridor safer by reducing speeds.

I do think improvements could be made southbound where you are in danger if driving from Woodall Rogers to I-45 south and you have to change lanes to the left in a short amount of time.
Nothing will improve the highway safety until they lower speed limits.  Who thinks 70 mph (US75) is a safe speed limit inside city/suburb limits?
